==English==
===Etymology===
Old English ''[[wēod]]''
====Noun====
'''weed''' (''[[countable]] and [[uncountable]]''; ''plural'' '''weeds''')

#(''countable'') Any [[plant]] growing in [[cultivated]] ground to the injury of the [[crop]] or desired vegetation, or to the disfigurement of the place; an unsightly, useless, or injurious plant.
#(''countable''; ''informal'') A [[puny]] person; one who has with little physical strength.
#(''uncountable'') [[Tobacco]].
#(''countable'') A [[cigar]].
#(''uncountable''; ''slang'') [[Marijuana]].
#(''countable'') A garment; clothing; especially, an upper or outer garment.
#(''countable'') An article of dress worn in token of [[grief]]; a [[mourning]] garment or badge; as, he wore a weed on his hat; especially, in the plural, mourning garb, as of a woman.
#:''widow's weeds''
#(''countable'') A sudden illness or [[relapse]], often attended with fever, which attacks women in childbed.
#(''uncountable'') Underbrush; low shrubs.
#(''countable''; ''figuratively'') Something unprofitable or troublesome; anything useless.
#(''countable'') An animal unfit to breed from.

